00:38:26.270 --> 00:38:39.690
Raúl Kripalani: And I think it's every 256 epochs, or, like, there is… there was another number, I can't remember. Subnet… beacon nodes rotate which subnets they're actually giving structure to and servicing. So you can think of…

293
00:38:39.690 --> 00:38:55.839
Raúl Kripalani: subnets as being the backbone, the circulation, kind of like, you know, the veins through which attestations are circulating in the network. And as we all know, committee… attesters get assigned to one committee per epoch, to… to attest, once every epoch.

294
00:38:55.840 --> 00:39:18.570
Raúl Kripalani: So, as an attester is, calculating its, look-ahead epox, it is gonna say, I'm gonna, I'm gonna be pushing attestations on this particular subnet forever at whatever slot, and, it will need a way to be able to deliver those attestations to that subnet. Now, what happens in reality is that, we can't have

295
00:39:18.570 --> 00:39:24.749
Raúl Kripalani: So our testers are gonna be rotating committees every… Every, every epoch?

296
00:39:25.050 --> 00:39:26.130
Raúl Kripalani: And…

297
00:39:26.130 --> 00:39:51.040
Raúl Kripalani: we can't… so if attesters were the ones that were creating and giving substance to those subnets, we would be having a lot of volatility in the network, because basically we would be having a network. The backbone of the network would be reshuffling, every 32 slots, and that creates a lot of instability. So the mechanism that we have is we decouple the backbone from the traffic that transits over that backbone. So, the backbone is those 64 subnets.

298
00:39:51.040 --> 00:40:10.599
Raúl Kripalani: nodes based on their PRID and based on a bunch of things, that's a deterministic formula. Calculate two subnets that they're gonna be giving structure to, so they're going to be subscribing and moving messages and forwarding messages, does not mean that they're actually going to test. These are beacon nodes. They might not actually be running any validators behind them to begin with.

299
00:40:10.600 --> 00:40:20.120
Raúl Kripalani: So these are just beacon nodes, they give substance to those subnets, and then testers are sending emitting attestations on those subnets, right? So we have this dual structure.

