00:40:20.290 --> 00:40:27.669
Raúl Kripalani: And what happens is that, if you run the math, the chances, of, of…

301
00:40:27.860 --> 00:40:52.080
Raúl Kripalani: having attestations come from inside the mesh or inside the subnets for a particular committee is tiny. It's just a 3%, right? So, for every given slot, you look at the nodes that would be servicing those subnets, and the nodes that would be attesting, and it's just a 3% overlap. So, in reality, most of the attestations are coming from outside those subnets into the subnet through

302
00:40:52.090 --> 00:41:15.650
Raúl Kripalani: what in at least the Go implementation of GoSubSub is called FanOut, this fan-out mechanism. And just to give you some magnitude of, some, some magnitudes here, currently, if you take the 1 million attesters, you divide them into 32, 30, 32 slots, and you divide them into committees, you're gonna get to the point where you have around 515 attestations per subnet per slot, so…

303
00:41:15.650 --> 00:41:34.670
Raúl Kripalani: 515 attestations per committee. These attestations are tiny. They are 180 or 200 bytes once you compress them. They don't compress too well, because the one… a big part of it is the signature, but the rest does.

304
00:41:34.680 --> 00:41:47.909
Raúl Kripalani: And there's actually a good compression factor if you're able to, batch multiple attestations at once, because those attestations will be having common fields across them. So…

305
00:41:47.910 --> 00:42:00.069
Raúl Kripalani: Just to give you a sense of magnitude here, currently we have for every committee, we would be having around 100K of unique data transiting… transiting over the, over the subnet, for that committee.

