00:43:38.610 --> 00:43:41.690
Raúl Kripalani: Then I must need to have 8…

316
00:43:41.690 --> 00:43:47.399
Raúl Kripalani: a factor of 8 less messages, right, in the network. That's kind of like the naive way of saying it. So really.

317
00:43:47.540 --> 00:44:01.340
Raúl Kripalani: the causal effect here that this is pursuing is really the reduction in traffic and the ability to move those attestations, in time, to where they need to be. So…

318
00:44:01.410 --> 00:44:14.990
Raúl Kripalani: this is the physical… so going from 1 million attesters to 128 attesters is kind of like the physical way of achieving that, right? But what if there is a virtual way, right? So you just keep a million attesters.

319
00:44:14.990 --> 00:44:21.819
Raúl Kripalani: But instead, you allow them to consolidate and pre-aggregate their attestations at source.

320
00:44:21.890 --> 00:44:38.380
Raúl Kripalani: So this is something that the protocol should have been doing since the beginning, but it was way harder for different reasons, and they weren't good mechanisms to defend against permutations that could appear in the network. The problem here is

321
00:44:38.380 --> 00:44:47.230
Raúl Kripalani: If you're gonna be allowing messages in the network, attestations in the network, do not represent a single attestation.

322
00:44:47.280 --> 00:44:48.989
Raúl Kripalani: But to actually group

323
00:44:49.110 --> 00:45:03.840
Raúl Kripalani: multiple attestations within them, you could… an attacker could come in and try and dynamically recombine the attestations that they're seeing flying about in the network to form new, unique messages, right? So you have this, like.

324
00:45:03.870 --> 00:45:15.599
Raúl Kripalani: infinite… not infinite, but, like, like, very highly bounded universe for permutations, right, of those attestations. And that basically translates to spam in the network.

325
00:45:16.900 --> 00:45:31.760
Raúl Kripalani: So, there's a proposal, it's called Batched attestations at Source. We might rename it to Pre-Agregating attestations at Source. We don't want to call it Aggregating attest… don't want to call it aggregate… Aggregating.

326
00:45:31.820 --> 00:45:44.620
Raúl Kripalani: Only because that has a very specific term in the protocol, and this is not… not what's happening here. So yeah, so we may… we might back out of this name and just call it pre-aggregating, because that's really, really what's happening.

327
00:45:44.730 --> 00:46:01.980
Raúl Kripalani: So, the key unlock here is… okay, so how do we prevent, so the idea here is that instead of sending a single, every validator in a committee, sending a single, attestation to the network.

328
00:46:02.140 --> 00:46:12.610
Raúl Kripalani: You allow those beacon nodes that are running multiple validators behind them to pre-aggregate at source before they emit the message to the network.

329
00:46:12.630 --> 00:46:30.069
Raúl Kripalani: So this is already happening today. If you look at all… like, it's already happening that beacon nodes are collecting, are collecting the attestations from their validator clients. So really, this would just introduce one step that would be transparent,

330
00:46:30.070 --> 00:46:41.370
Raúl Kripalani: almost transparent to the validators themselves. So the idea here is that you would have…

331
00:46:41.580 --> 00:46:53.460
Raúl Kripalani: For those validators that are attesting at the same… at a particular committee at the same point in time, you would pre-aggregate their… their attestations at source, and then sign over them.

332
00:46:53.560 --> 00:47:07.549
Raúl Kripalani: And there is a two-way binding, to make this secure, so that that attestation, that aggregate attestation, cannot be recombined with other attestations in the network without it being very obvious that there was,

333
00:47:07.560 --> 00:47:22.060
Raúl Kripalani: some malicious actor, doing… doing something, because this cannot happen in a… in a… in a benign way. So the way that that mechanism works is you have the notion of a batcher, so the batcher is…

334
00:47:22.240 --> 00:47:23.380
Raúl Kripalani: one of…

335
00:47:23.530 --> 00:47:32.789
Raúl Kripalani: the validators that are, say, for example, you have… you're an operator, you're a large operator, a validator pool, or dbt, and you are…

336
00:47:34.020 --> 00:47:46.940
Raúl Kripalani: managing, let's say, 50 validators that are gonna attest on… that happen to attest on the same committee. So, normally, you would send 50 messages to the network. With this, you send one.

337
00:47:47.130 --> 00:47:59.210
Raúl Kripalani: So what you do is you find out who those validators are, and from those validators, one of them is gonna be the batcher, so it's gonna be an endorser of the batch.

338
00:47:59.400 --> 00:48:05.699
Raúl Kripalani: It has to be, and this is an important invariant here, it has to be one of the participants in the committee.

339
00:48:05.860 --> 00:48:13.569
Raúl Kripalani: In that signature, in that pre-aggregated signature. So then, what you do is you take…

340
00:48:13.770 --> 00:48:17.920
Raúl Kripalani: Every attester is gonna create a batch seal.

341
00:48:18.100 --> 00:48:24.260
Raúl Kripalani: Consenting to be included in the batch that is going to be signed by the batcher.

342
00:48:24.320 --> 00:48:39.480
Raúl Kripalani: And then, once the batcher has collected the signatures it wants to include, it is going to aggregate them, and then they're gonna seal their whole… they're gonna put a signature over that, that aggregate.

343
00:48:39.590 --> 00:48:42.360
Raúl Kripalani: So now, this has some nice effects.

344
00:48:42.510 --> 00:48:47.870
Raúl Kripalani: In that, with this data structure, the validation becomes

